Évaluation publiée le 13 novembre 2021
The game got updated since my previous review, so I'll update this review in tandem.
Although I've changed my rating from a negative to a positive, the game still feels like it needs a LOT more fine-tuning before it actually feels ready to play.

The game's flow feels kinda fun, and I see a lot of potential in this title, but there's still a lot of things that need polish.

The textures feel very sloppy, and there's a bunch of mechanics later on that feel poorly conveyed (ex, moving platforms that encourage you to jump off for high speeds, but stop unexpectedly)

The game's main mechanic is the ability to push/pull weightless cubes, and occasionally platforming on them as well. It's a cool concept that could certainly go interesting places, but it never really feels like it reaches it's full potential.

I'd say the mechanic could definitely use some more tweaking before it feels right, in both under-the-hood adjustments and better level design to encourage more interesting use of it. I think the optimal experience would be having to pulling a bunch of cubes in front of me in order to platform across a large gap. Unfortunately, the mechanics don't allow enough control for this to be possible, and the level design never sets the player up for a situation like this, either.

Great potential, but a great amount of work still needs to be done.

I find the game to be fun when things work properly. It is a demo for an ambitious game so I can't complain at the moment.
I think the issue is that the game requires a high precision for movement, specifically wall movement, but it is a bit funky and doesn't work all the time (mostly because of the running issue that I will explain next).
Either make running the default movement, or by pressing down on the button (PC mouse and keyboard is shift), because toggle run doesn't work well with the wall mechanic and causes most of the failures.
I have encountered several bugs such as the one where my push/pull no longer worked, and did fall through an elevator once.

I got as far as the middle (I think) of the red level (blue, green, red, as it went) and going back to the precision part, it was just getting to the point of suffering because of toggle run has no room in this game (make it a button you push to run, but not toggle on/off, cant stress this enough).

Overall, from the demo, the game development it is heading in a good direction.

Played it for a bit. Didn't have fun. The level designs weren't all that spectacular to me. The wall running felt stale and boring, the puzzles were very basic, and the overall movement felt clunky.

Movement is important in a parkour game. While playing this game, it was both somewhat accurate but still iffy. Wall running, as I mentioned, is stale. I don't feel anything with wall-running; in fact, I felt nothing while playing this game. No excitement, nothing. Oh wait, I did feel frustration. The last level was just boring and frustrating. I guess you can say it left an impression on me.

To pretty much sum it up: this game is unexciting. I feel more excited when riding an elevator to the 2nd floor than from playing this game. I feel more satisfied cracking a knuckle than completing a level. It was actually a chore to finish, but at least it wasn't an outright horrendous chore that made me want to shoot myself 5 times in the chest.

To list some of the bugs/issues I've encountered:
- Sprinting is a joke. The shift key is a toggle for sprint, but you have to retoggle it whenever you get back on the ground.
- When wall running, your camera is angled. Very prevalent in the last level was your camera not fixing itself when wall running towards the end of the level
- There is 0 customization/optimization for this game. I cannot change my graphics quality, change my volume, nothing of that sort. "But it's a free game" is a useless reason because many free yet short games have these incredibly basic functions
- Simply not fun, at least for me

I can never say whether you, whoever is reading this, can enjoy this game. What I've expressed is purely my opinion. It's a free game, so you can check it out for yourself to figure out whether or not you'd like it.

Just note one important thing:
This game is the prelude to the actual game, which is $8. Sadly enough, this free demo they've brought up gives me no reason to ever consider buying their actual game, except for the sake of reviewing it and telling others if it's actually worth it.
So far, in this demo, I will say it's not worth it. But who knows! If ya liked it, ya liked it. That's it. I just didn't like this game at all.

Évaluation publiée le 4 juillet 2020
Fun concept, but definitely needs improvement.

After playing through the first couple of levels the impression that I got was that it has potential to be a very fun game, but has some glaring flaws. First off, I will say that the game looks great (visually) despite its simplicity. The music is also catchy and fits it well. The game seems like it could be incredibly fun if polished up a bit, but right now I cant overlook some of the problems that made it frustrating to play. The first thing that I noticed upon starting to play is that the movement speed in this game (even while sprinting) is surprisingly slow. I feel that this game would be much more fun if it were slightly faster paced. the maps/puzzles seem to be well thought out, but at the slow speed it wasn't as entertaining.

The bigger issue would be some of the bugs and/or design decisions. The most frustrating design decision made in this game was to set the sprint button up as a toggle. It wouldn't be as much of an issue if not for the fact that it automatically untoggles if you stop or rapidly change direction. Many if not most of my difficulties in this game were due to the sprint function not working as I intended for it to, as many of the jumps do require you to sprint for them, and when it randomly turns off you are left to fall and die and try again.

The second most frustrating issue would have to be the wall run mechanics, which are bluntly put unrefined. often times you wont snap to a wall at all when attempting to, and simply fall and die. In addition to this, you are automatically ejected from the wall if you angle your view too far outward, which can make it difficult to manage certain jumps. This is also a very frustrating design choice.

The final major issue I noticed is that after a certain point (or perhaps certain number of uses?) I lost the ability to use the push/pull function entirely. I am unsure if this is a bug or is intended, but it certainly is needed in certain parts of the game and if its meant to be that way, some sort of use gauge would be a welcome addition.

Finally, this game is surprisingly hardware intensive for a game with such simple (although great looking graphics). My GTX1660Ti was at nearly 100% usage my entire time playing this game. This is harder on the graphics card than many if not most other modern games (even when running the other games on high or even ultra). I'm not sure why that is, but it definitely turned my PC into a space heater.

Overall the game has great potential and could be incredibly fun with some polishing up, but at the point the game is at now, I cant say I would recommend it.

It's a fun and (at the moment short) game. Finished it in about half an hour, as for my recommendations...

- While the push and pull mechanic is interesting, it feels as if it was just plastered onto the game unnecessarily and isn't integrated to be a part of the game. It should be used in more dynamic ways which feel natural as opposed to "push the wall away". You should build upon being a parkour game and focus on being able to keep your flow going instead of having to stop to check which blocks are solid and which fall.

-One thing that disappointed me was that whenever you build up a lot of speed from say a moving platform, upon touching ground again you lose all that speed which makes it feel like you're losing your flow. I'd suggest keeping momentum when touching the ground and wall running as it feels funner and definitely faster.

Évaluation publiée le 16 janvier 2023
Это демо игры про паркур и бессмысленно расставленные кубы.

В игре есть механика PUSH и PULL;
Используя одну из них, мы взаимодействуем с кубами.
Кубы.. ну, они есть и это единственное на что распространяется закон гравитации ( кроме персонажа ).
Так вот, механика push/pull взаимодействует с кубами, а кубы расставлены так, что в 90% можно было бы обойтись без них.

Паркур. 50/50 - бег по стенам ( специальная текстура стен ) / бег по платформам.

Дизайн локаций часто сделан так, что не ясно "Куда теперь?".

В итоге; есть две механики, которые привязаны друг к другу, бег по стенам. Хромой левел дизайн.
Посмотрев такую демку, я не стал бы покупать полную версию.

⮞ Полное прохождение демки 28 минут.

Évaluation publiée le 26 octobre 2020
'ery nice!
Why so?

  • Great performance, everything runs smoothly.
  • Great pacing at levels, you never get bored. Obstacles are easy to recognize, and there's enough room for you to react to them in real-time.
  • Good controls, it's easy to land precise jumps.
  • Good wall-running/jumping. An intuitive way of running on walls and jumping from them.
  • Good audio feedback. You can hear your steps and clearly understand in you landed or not on something.
  • Though, would be nice to have some additional sounds (like double jump)
  • Respawning. Who would have thought that it matters? But apparently, it does. In this game, you don't need to wait for half-minute to retry some jump. Though, some indication of save points, audio/visual, would be even better.
  • Unobtrusive lore. You may skip bits of it if you want, but you are provided with pieces of information throughout the levels.
  • Great level designs. Absolutely love the use of cubes that you need to push, the fact that you can jump from them, original obstacles (like a curtain of some orange things. Love it, wish there were more of those).
Try this game for free, and if you like it, go and support devs on their following project "Vectromirror".
Don't expect the same quality though.
Yet, this game was excellent. Gonna replay it more with the speedrun timer on now :D

Évaluation publiée le 26 septembre 2020
TL;DR: Fun parkour game, with a few flaws. Play it with a controller.
Would happily play the full game when it comes out.

The bad, mostly/entirely technical stuff:
First: The controls don't match the instructions.
On the gamepad (Mine is a wired 360 controller) the instructions say sprint is L3. It's actually X.
Alongside that, Push and Pull controls are reversed. Neither are difficult to work around, especially with a toggle sprint.
The same is not true for K&M. The movement keys work, but that's about it. At least- for me. I tested with a keyboard and mouse while the controller was still plugged in. I could look around and move with the arrow keys, but that's it.
Second: Sprinting is picky.
I haven't pinned down what causes the sprint to stop, my guess is speed- or a lack thereof. One instance where it bit me in the butt is the giant orange death-pit section. There's a steep ramp that goes to a wallrun; I could neither sprint nor jump on the ramp.

The so-so: Mechanical quirks.
Another instance where the instructions don't match the gameplay: you don't actually need sprint to wall-run.
You just need to run at the wall while facing vaguely in the direction you want to go, and you'll go that way full-speed. On top of this it resets your double-jump. Once you get used to this (and are done with the curved walls) it's very fun.
Your first jump is forgiving, your second jump is not.
You can walk off an edge and have a short window to jump and still have your second jump. This and the above saved me on the ramp mentioned above.
Your second jump resets your vertical momentum. Good for falls, bad for launch pads.
The maps-
For the red gates level the issue is just checkpoint placement. You have to backtrack a bit at the floating-block-navigating section, if you die in that section, in order to open the gate. Not difficult, there's even a ramp to get to that point but I'd rather restart from there.
For the orange death room level it's at the very top of that same room I keep mentioning. When you land up there and turn around, the obvious path is wallrunning to the far side. That path leads nowhere. It's actually under the sign.

The good:
The push/pull mechanics.
Brilliantly done. Minus the tutorial (Easier to just jump on the blocks at either side) and instruction mismatch, these and the blocks that go with are very fun to play with. If you make another game akin to this, do experiment with player-enacted level manipulation.
The movement.
Nowhere near as bad as people say. Good air control, responsive, lofty jumps. Hope you have workshop and map-making tools on release of the full game, this has potential.
The maps- everything I've yet to mention.
There's... Not much to say here. The freedom of movement is mostly utilized in the maps, even in the areas mentioned above. At a minimum they're solid and fun, on average they're the right kind of challenging, and at best you'll want to replay levels a few times just because the routes you find or come up with are that fun.

Évaluation publiée le 15 aout 2020
A fun platformer that introduces an cool mechainc that will hopefully have more uses in the next game.

The platfomring in this game is a little janky, the most major issues i found where wall running was a hit or miss, and sometimes i'd clip into the wallrunning wall. My double jump randomly not working when wallrunning or when just simply standing. the pull mechanic is terrible, having to pull a cube about 10 times just so it can move a few inches in the wrong direction just got annoying so i just gave up on using it. The sprint would consistently stop working while jumping or mid air or even wallrunning, i found that clicking shift again would start the running again even if your in the air or on the ground. The push and pull mechanic felt like for of an annoyance and put a stop to the fast paced gameplay alot of the times. The last level is annoying and hardly challenging because of the part where you have to guess which blocks are solid, and only stay soild for a little bit of time, wasn't challenging at all just made it painful to play.

I hope that in the next game the pull and push thing is worked on more, as it seemed useless in this game to the point where i hardly used it even when the path was blocked, id just walk through or jump around.
